    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-02-08T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-02-08T04:00:00-05:00" n="17"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d17">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8509: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The First Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Merrill</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-02-08T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 8, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 8—2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>54. 1. Sung Che Yuan and the commander of the Japanese North China garrison are
                    conversing periodically at Tientsin. Chinese and Japanese officials state that
                    the conversations are probably confined to economic cooperation. It is
                    understood that the Japanese are primarily interested at present in the
                    questions of (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) developing the Lungyen iron mines in
                    Chahar and the Chingying coal mines in Western Hopei and (<hi rend="italic"
                        >b</hi>) constructing the Shihkiachwang Railway.</p>
                <p>2. Apparently no progress is being made toward an increase of autonomy in North
                    China. Sung Che Yuan is said by Japanese to have become more conciliatory toward
                    them during the detention of Chiang Kai-shek at Sian but to have reverted to his
                    previous attitude after Chiang’s release.</p>
                <p>3. Fresh and significant developments in North China presumably await (<hi
                        rend="italic">a</hi>) clarification of the situation created in China by the
                    trouble in Sian and (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) clarification of the political
                    situation at Tokyo.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Merrill</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
